<paragraph id="8BC636A1D175FFC6688A2C84FB81FEFE" blockId="4.[166,1225,1717,1839]" lastBlockId="5.[174,1233,175,810]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="424" pageId="4" pageNumber="423">
S t r a t i g r a p h i c a l r a n g e. Apart from the 
<typeStatus id="54C28803D175FFC76AB92C84FCDEF8F8" box="[744,793,1781,1807]" pageId="4" pageNumber="423">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D175FFC76BC52C84FB88F8F8" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[916,1103,1781,1807]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="4" pageNumber="423" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D175FFC76BC52C84FB88F8F8" box="[916,1103,1781,1807]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="423">Gryphoca similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D175FFC768F72D64FED3F8D8" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[166,276,1813,1839]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="4" pageNumber="423" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D175FFC768F72D64FED3F8D8" box="[166,276,1813,1839]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="423">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from the Pliocene (Scaldisian) of the Antwerp area, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D175FFC76B9D2D64FBE8F8D8" box="[972,1071,1813,1839]" name="Belgium" pageId="4" pageNumber="423">Belgium</collectingCountry>
, from the late Miocene (early-middle Tortonian, 8.0–11.5 ma) Gram Formation of Gram, Jutland, western 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC668FF2ABEFED8FF1E" box="[174,287,207,233]" name="Denmark" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Denmark</collectingCountry>
, from the late Miocene or early Pliocene of Mill-Langenboom, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66C592ABEFB0BFF1E" box="[1032,1228,207,233]" name="Netherlands" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">The Netherlands</collectingCountry>
, and from the Pliocene (5.0–5.8 ma) Yorktown Formation, eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66BF72A9EFB85FEFE" box="[934,1090,239,265]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">United States</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22B61FC37FE9D" blockId="5.[174,1233,175,810]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
R e f e r r e d m a t e r i a l. Humeri, scapula, innominate, femora, tibia and fibula from the Antwerp area, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC669862B5EFDFBFEBE" box="[471,572,303,329]" name="Belgium" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Belgium</collectingCountry>
, from western 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66AA72B5EFCAEFEBE" box="[758,873,303,329]" name="Denmark" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Denmark</collectingCountry>
, from Mill-Langenboom, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66CF52B5EFE86FE9E" name="Netherlands" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">The Netherlands</collectingCountry>
, and from the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66A162B3EFD23FE9E" box="[583,740,335,361]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D174FFC66AA22B3EFC24FE9D" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[755,995,335,362]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky, Ray, 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22B01FCE0FDBE" blockId="5.[174,1233,175,810]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
E m e n d e d d i a g n o s i s. Phocine of medium size similar to modern 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66C142B1EFF3DFE5E" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1791" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Halichoerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grypus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66C142B1EFF3DFE5E" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Halichoerus grypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Deltoid crest of humerus short, narrow, and thin, terminating about 1/2 length of bone; its distal end gently broadening and somewhat overhanging the bone; lesser tubercle located slightly above head and proximal part of deltoid crest; intertubercular groove narrow and deep; medial epicondyle reaches distal end of deltoid crest; entepicondylar foramen present. Femoral greater trochanter higher than head; minimal width of shaft located in middle part of femur; epicondyles very thin
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D174FFC668B22821FBA2FCDE" blockId="5.[174,1233,175,810]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
D i s c u s s i o n. The rare taxon 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66A39283EFCE8FD9E" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[616,815,591,617]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66A39283EFCE8FD9E" box="[616,815,591,617]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Gryphoca similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is represented in Van Beneden’s collection only by a few fragmentary bones: humeri and femora, scapula, innominate, tibia and fibula. All bones show very distinctive morphological features and the same applies to the material from the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66AD228DEFCE6FD3E" box="[643,801,687,713]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D174FFC66B6128DEFBE6FD3D" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[816,1057,687,714]" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky, Ray, 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Although the morphologies of the fossils from Western 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66ACA28BEFCCCFD1E" box="[667,779,719,745]" name="Denmark" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">Denmark</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D174FFC66B1428BEFBCEFD1E" box="[837,1033,719,745]" name="Netherlands" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">The Netherlands</collectingCountry>
described in this paper are very similar, the bones also differ in several aspects. Nonetheless, we are sure about the assignment of these new fossils to a new species of the genus 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D174FFC66BBC297EFBA2FCDE" box="[1005,1125,783,809]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="424">
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D174FFC66BBC297EFBA6FCDE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[1005,1121,783,809]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gryphoca</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
